{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:54:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1411"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1411"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.12,0.16,0.03,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106435"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1411"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88891"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"628"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"9677"},{"type":"tags","id":"9679"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1618"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106435"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents with bilateral nasal congestion for the last six weeks. In this time, he also has itching of the nose and eyes. He has trialled oral cetirizine 1 tablet daily for the past four weeks which has resulted in some improvement, though he is still bothered by them. He reports that over the last few years he has had similar symptoms episodically over, usually around spring-time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would be the most appropriate addition to current therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral prednisolone for 5 days","Oral montelukast","Oxymetazoline nasal spray","Oral amoxicillin for 7 days","Fluticasone nasal spray"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a classic presentation of acute allergic rhinitis, describing intermittent symptoms that are exacerbated around high-pollen seasons. Symptoms can include rhinorrhoea, nasal congestion, itching of the nose and sneezing. In this case, the patient also describes allergic conjunctivitis. A history of atopy may be present, including allergic dermatitis, asthma or food allergies. Oral or intranasal antihistamines are recommended as a first-line treatment, which this patient has already initiated. For patients that do not have adequate relief with antihistamine use, the addition of intranasal corticosteroid such as \u003Cstrong\u003Efluticasone\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Enasal spray\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E Intranasal corticosteroids are particularly effective in treating the symptom of nasal congestion, so this is the best option for this particular patient. Additionally, they can also reduce symptoms of allergic conjunctivitis. Whilst improvement in symptoms is usually seen within a few days, it is recommended patients adhere to a trial of treatment for at least 4 weeks before it can be deemed ineffective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMontelukast\u003C/strong\u003E is a leukotrine receptor antagonist that is a useful addition to antihistamines and intranasal steroids. Montelukast can be particularly effective for patients that have co-existing asthma and allergic rhinitis, but it can cause unpleasant side effects including depression, sleep disturbances and agitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxymetazoline nasal spray\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of nasal decongestant. Oral or intranasal decongestants do not have a role in the management of allergic rhinitis, though can be effective for patients reporting acute viral nasal congestion. They should not be used for more than 3-5 days as they cause a rebound increase in nasal congestion and there are potential cardiovascular side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin for 7 days \u003C/strong\u003Eis not indicated for this patient, as there are no features suggesting a bacterial cause of sinusitis. If the patient described symptoms consistent with an infective cause of sinusitis, it would most likely be due to a viral pathogen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA course of \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral prednisolone for 5 days\u003C/strong\u003E is a recommended treatment for \u003Cem\u003Echronic\u003C/em\u003E rhinosinusitis, as opposed to acute rhinitis as is the case for this patient. Chronic rhinosinusitis is defined as the presence of symptoms for 12 or more weeks. First line treatment is nasal irrigation with sodium chloride which should be trialled for 4 weeks, prior to consideration of further investigation, specialist review and prednisolone for refractory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An intranasal corticosteroid is appropriate second-line treatment for allergic rhinitis."],"references":["Siddiqui ZA, Walker A, Pirwani MM, et al. Allergic rhinitis: diagnosis and management. Br J Hosp Med (Lond) . 2022; 83:1-9. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35243888/","Gunda D, Mustafa J, Agar N, Goss P. Approach to allergic rhinitis in the primary care setting. Aust J Gen Pract. 2024;53(11 Suppl):S3-S7. doi:10.31128/AJGP-07-23-6890. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2024/supplement-november/approach-to-allergic-rhinitis-in-the-primary-care"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88891"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1411"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88891"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T20:16:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T20:16:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1411"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106435"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:4